IP(8)                                                                                                                        Linux                                                                                                                       IP(8)

NNAAMMEE
       ip - show / manipulate routing, network devices, interfaces and tunnels

SSYYNNOOPPSSIISS
       iipp [ _O_P_T_I_O_N_S ] _O_B_J_E_C_T { _C_O_M_M_A_N_D | hheellpp }

       iipp [ --ffoorrccee ] --bbaattcchh _f_i_l_e_n_a_m_e

       _O_B_J_E_C_T := { lliinnkk | aaddddrreessss | aaddddrrllaabbeell | rroouuttee | rruullee | nneeiigghh | nnttaabbllee | ttuunnnneell | ttuunnttaapp | mmaaddddrreessss | mmrroouuttee | mmrruullee | mmoonniittoorr | xxffrrmm | nneettnnss | ll22ttpp | ttccpp__mmeettrriiccss | ttookkeenn | mmaaccsseecc }

       _O_P_T_I_O_N_S := { --VV[_e_r_s_i_o_n] | --hh[_u_m_a_n_-_r_e_a_d_a_b_l_e] | --ss[_t_a_t_i_s_t_i_c_s] | --dd[_e_t_a_i_l_s] | --rr[_e_s_o_l_v_e] | --iieecc | --ff[_a_m_i_l_y] { iinneett | iinneett66 | lliinnkk } | --44 | --66 | --II | --DD | --BB | --00 | --ll[_o_o_p_s] { mmaaxxiimmuumm--aaddddrr--fflluusshh--aatttteemmppttss } | --oo[_n_e_l_i_n_e] | --rrcc[_v_b_u_f] [ssiizzee] | --tt[_i_m_e_s_‐
               _t_a_m_p] | --ttss[_h_o_r_t] | --nn[_e_t_n_s] name | --NN[_u_m_e_r_i_c] | --aa[_l_l] | --cc[_o_l_o_r] | --bbrr[_i_e_f] | --jj[son] | --pp[retty] }

OOPPTTIIOONNSS
       --VV, --VVeerrssiioonn
              Print the version of the iipp utility and exit.

       --hh, --hhuummaann, --hhuummaann--rreeaaddaabbllee
              output statistics with human readable values followed by suffix.

       --bb, --bbaattcchh <FILENAME>
              Read commands from provided file or standard input and invoke them.  First failure will cause termination of ip.

       --ffoorrccee Don't terminate ip on errors in batch mode.  If there were any errors during execution of the commands, the application return code will be non zero.

       --ss, --ssttaattss, --ssttaattiissttiiccss
              Output more information. If the option appears twice or more, the amount of information increases.  As a rule, the information is statistics or some time values.

       --dd, --ddeettaaiillss
              Output more detailed information.

       --ll, --llooooppss <COUNT>
              Specify maximum number of loops the 'ip address flush' logic will attempt before giving up. The default is 10.  Zero (0) means loop until all addresses are removed.

       --ff, --ffaammiillyy <FAMILY>
              Specifies the protocol family to use. The protocol family identifier can be one of iinneett, iinneett66, bbrriiddggee, mmppllss or lliinnkk.  If this option is not present, the protocol family is guessed from other arguments. If the rest of the command line does
              not give enough information to guess the family, iipp falls back to the default one, usually iinneett or aannyy.  lliinnkk is a special family identifier meaning that no networking protocol is involved.

       --44     shortcut for --ffaammiillyy iinneett.

       --66     shortcut for --ffaammiillyy iinneett66.

       --BB     shortcut for --ffaammiillyy bbrriiddggee.

       --MM     shortcut for --ffaammiillyy mmppllss.

       --00     shortcut for --ffaammiillyy lliinnkk.

       --oo, --oonneelliinnee
              output each record on a single line, replacing line feeds with the ''\\'' character. This is convenient when you want to count records with wwcc(1) or to ggrreepp(1) the output.

       --rr, --rreessoollvvee
              use the system's name resolver to print DNS names instead of host addresses.

       --nn, --nneettnnss <NETNS>
              switches iipp to the specified network namespace _N_E_T_N_S.  Actually it just simplifies executing of:

              iipp nneettnnss eexxeecc _N_E_T_N_S iipp [ _O_P_T_I_O_N_S ] _O_B_J_E_C_T { _C_O_M_M_A_N_D | hheellpp }

              to

              iipp -n[etns] _N_E_T_N_S [ _O_P_T_I_O_N_S ] _O_B_J_E_C_T { _C_O_M_M_A_N_D | hheellpp }

       --NN, --NNuummeerriicc
              Print the number of protocol, scope, dsfield, etc directly instead of converting it to human readable name.

       --aa, --aallll
              executes specified command over all objects, it depends if command supports this option.

       --cc[ccoolloorr][=={aallwwaayyss|aauuttoo|nneevveerr}
              Configure color output. If parameter is omitted or aallwwaayyss, color output is enabled regardless of stdout state. If parameter is aauuttoo, stdout is checked to be a terminal before enabling color output. If parameter is nneevveerr, color output is
              disabled. If specified multiple times, the last one takes precedence. This flag is ignored if --jjssoonn is also given.

              Used color palette can be influenced by CCOOLLOORRFFGGBBGG environment variable (see EENNVVIIRROONNMMEENNTT).

       --tt, --ttiimmeessttaammpp
              display current time when using monitor option.

       --ttss, --ttsshhoorrtt
              Like --ttiimmeessttaammpp, but use shorter format.

       --rrcc, --rrccvvbbuuff<SIZE>
              Set the netlink socket receive buffer size, defaults to 1MB.

       --iieecc   print human readable rates in IEC units (e.g. 1Ki = 1024).

       --bbrr, --bbrriieeff
              Print only basic information in a tabular format for better readability. This option is currently only supported by iipp aaddddrr sshhooww and iipp lliinnkk sshhooww commands.

       --jj, --jjssoonn
              Output results in JavaScript Object Notation (JSON).

       --pp, --pprreettttyy
              The default JSON format is compact and more efficient to parse but hard for most users to read.  This flag adds indentation for readability.

IIPP -- CCOOMMMMAANNDD SSYYNNTTAAXX
   _O_B_J_E_C_T
       aaddddrreessss
              - protocol (IP or IPv6) address on a device.

       aaddddrrllaabbeell
              - label configuration for protocol address selection.

       ll22ttpp   - tunnel ethernet over IP (L2TPv3).

       lliinnkk   - network device.

       mmaaddddrreessss
              - multicast address.

       mmoonniittoorr
              - watch for netlink messages.

       mmrroouuttee - multicast routing cache entry.

       mmrruullee  - rule in multicast routing policy database.

       nneeiigghhbboouurr
              - manage ARP or NDISC cache entries.

       nneettnnss  - manage network namespaces.

       nnttaabbllee - manage the neighbor cache's operation.

       rroouuttee  - routing table entry.

       rruullee   - rule in routing policy database.

       ttccpp__mmeettrriiccss//ttccppmmeettrriiccss
              - manage TCP Metrics

       ttookkeenn  - manage tokenized interface identifiers.

       ttuunnnneell - tunnel over IP.

       ttuunnttaapp - manage TUN/TAP devices.

       xxffrrmm   - manage IPSec policies.

       The names of all objects may be written in full or abbreviated form, for example aaddddrreessss can be abbreviated as aaddddrr or just aa..

   _C_O_M_M_A_N_D
       Specifies the action to perform on the object.  The set of possible actions depends on the object type.  As a rule, it is possible to aadddd, ddeelleettee and sshhooww (or lliisstt ) objects, but some objects do not allow all of these operations or have some addi‐
       tional commands. The hheellpp command is available for all objects. It prints out a list of available commands and argument syntax conventions.

       If no command is given, some default command is assumed.  Usually it is lliisstt or, if the objects of this class cannot be listed, hheellpp.

EENNVVIIRROONNMMEENNTT
       CCOOLLOORRFFGGBBGG
              If set, it's value is used for detection whether background is dark or light and use contrast colors for it.

              COLORFGBG environment variable usually contains either two or three values separated by semicolons; we want the last value in either case.  If this value is 0-6 or 8, chose colors suitable for dark background:

              COLORFGBG=";0" ip -c a

EEXXIITT SSTTAATTUUSS
       Exit status is 0 if command was successful, and 1 if there is a syntax error.  If an error was reported by the kernel exit status is 2.

EEXXAAMMPPLLEESS
       ip addr
           Shows addresses assigned to all network interfaces.

       ip neigh
           Shows the current neighbour table in kernel.

       ip link set x up
           Bring up interface x.

       ip link set x down
           Bring down interface x.

       ip route
           Show table routes.

HHIISSTTOORRYY
       iipp was written by Alexey N. Kuznetsov and added in Linux 2.2.

